<BaseLayout
  title="Tuesday — Tiw | Nazaryah"
  description="The day-name Tuesday comes from Tiw, the Norse god of war and law. Here is who he was and why mapping his day onto Yahuah's calendar is a mistake."
>
  <article class="pg">
    <div class="pg-inner">

      <a href="/calendar" class="pg-back"><span class="arrow">←</span><span>Back to the Calendar</span></a>

      <header class="pg-header">
        <p class="pg-eyebrow">Tuesday</p>
        <h1 class="pg-title">Tiw</h1>
        <p class="pg-subtitle">Norse god of war, single combat, and law</p>
      </header>

      <p>
        Every Tuesday on the Gregorian calendar honors a Norse war-god. His name was <strong>Tiw</strong> (also called Týr in Old Norse, Tiwaz in older Germanic tongues), and he was worshiped across the Germanic world as the god of single combat, sworn oaths, and battle-justice.
      </p>

      <h2>Who He Was</h2>

      <p>
        Tiw was originally one of the highest gods of the Germanic peoples — in some accounts the chief god before Odin took that role. He was associated with war, with single combat between warriors, and with the binding force of sworn oaths. The most famous myth about him is the binding of the wolf Fenrir: when the gods needed someone to put a hand into the wolf's mouth as a pledge of good faith, Tiw was the only one willing. Fenrir bit it off, and Tiw became the one-handed god of broken oaths and the price of justice.
      </p>

      <p>
        When the Romans encountered the Germanic peoples, they identified Tiw with their war-god Mars — both were warriors, both were associated with combat. The Roman day of Mars (<em>dies Martis</em>) became, in the Germanic translation, the day of Tiw. Old English <em>Tiwesdæg</em> became Tuesday. In Romance languages the same day still bears the Latin form: French <em>mardi</em>, Italian <em>martedì</em>, Spanish <em>martes</em> — all from Mars.
      </p>

      <h2>Why It Matters</h2>

      <p>
        A god of war, combat, and battle-oaths is not a neutral name to carry through the week. Yahuah is called the Lord of Hosts — <em>Yahuah Tzevaot</em> — and He alone is the One who fights for His people.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Exodus 15:3</span> — "Yahuah is a man of war: Yahuah is his name."
      </div>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Deuteronomy 20:4</span> — "For Yahuah your Elohim is he that goeth with you, to fight for you against your enemies, to save you."
      </div>

      <p>
        The pagan world named a day for a war-god because they believed they needed his favor to win battles. Yahuah's people needed no such favor. The battles were His. The victories came from Him. To name a day for Tiw or Mars is to credit a creature for protection and triumph that belongs to the Creator.
      </p>

      <h2>Two Clocks That Cannot Be Mixed</h2>

      <p>
        Some will ask: <em>"What day in Yahuah's calendar is Tuesday really?"</em> The question itself misunderstands the two systems.
      </p>

      <p>
        Tuesday is a Roman day named after a Roman war-god, then renamed after a Norse war-god when the Germanic peoples adopted the Roman week. It belongs to Babylon's clock — the continuous seven-day rotation tied to pagan deities. Yahuah's clock does not have a Tuesday. Yahuah's days are counted from the new moon He hung in the heavens. The new moon is Day 1 of the month — a non-work day, though not a Sabbath. From there the days are numbered, and the Sabbaths fall on Days 8, 15, 22, and 29. When the next new moon appears, the count resets.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>There is no Tuesday in this system.</strong> Yahuah's days are counted from the new moon He set in the firmament — not from the name of a war-god whose stories the pagan world told around its fires. The Roman week and Yahuah's reckoning are two different clocks, running on different principles, and they do not translate into each other.
      </p>

      <h2>What to Do With It</h2>

      <p>
        Knowing where the name "Tuesday" came from does not necessarily mean a believer must stop saying it. But knowing the origin matters. Every time the third day of the Roman week is spoken, it carries the name of a god of broken oaths — a pagan deity worshiped for success in combat and sworn faithfulness. The faithful believer needs no such name. The Lord of Hosts goes with him into every battle, and no day on any calendar adds anything to that.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Yahuah's clock and Babylon's clock are not the same clock.</strong> The faithful watch the heavens and let the new moon tell them what day it is. The world watches its phone and lets a war-god tell it what day it is. The two answers are as far apart as east is from west.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-pull">
        Tuesday is Tiw's day. The Lord of Hosts knows nothing about him. Yahuah's days are counted from the new moon He set in the firmament — not from the name of a god who lost his hand to a wolf.
      </div>

